Sainsbury's plan to break through the British beauty market
Sainsbury's competes with Boots, Superdrug and Debenhams and sets up beauty departments where specialist assistants work, such as in large stores.
The initiative is part of a strategy to conquer the British beauty market, which is worth £2.8 billion and continues to grow, while the sale of fashion and household items continues to decline. The larger beauty departments are tested in 11 shops across the country. If they turn out to be a success, they will be introduced in even more shops next year.
The investment in the beauty market is also a result of the fact that supermarkets want to fill the shelves where TVs, microwaves and interior items once stood, with other products.
Sainsbury's plans to double its beauty offer and offer 3,000 products, including for the first time brands such as Revlon, Essie, Tweezerman and Dr. PawPaw.
The existing range of L'Oreal, Maybelline and Burt's Bees is also given more space, with display space per brand, such as in stores like Boots.
The supermarket also brings its Boutique make-up back on the market, now that most products are suitable for vegans, something younger shoppers increasingly demand.
In addition, perfumery the Fragrance Shop will test concessions in two shops of Sainsbury's. The first was opened in Croydon, in southern London, the second will be opened later this year in Selly Oak, Birmingham.
Because more and more people shop online and increasingly buy small amounts of food on a daily basis in local supermarkets, supermarkets need to make more efforts to convince people to shop with them.
Mike Coupe, Chief Executive of Sainsbury's, says that the stores will look more and more like warehouses, now that the supermarket chain is up against discounters Aldi and Lidl, with more services and non-food.
Sainsbury's has integrated Argos sales points into hundreds of stores and has also opened a number of Habitats since both chains were taken over two years ago. According to the company, the sale of food has increased and the acquisitions have yielded more returns.
The last time the supermarket tried to give its departments Beauty and Pharmacy a makeover, that became a flop.
Sainsbury's tested a collaboration with Boots at the beginning of the 2000s, but the cooperation was terminated when a conflict arose over the distribution of the income from the pharmacy department in the supermarkets.
This is a new strategy since Sainsbury's 281 dispensaries in the shops three years ago sold £ 125 million to Celesio, owner of the Lloyds Pharmacy chain.
Lloyds would also play a role in the plan, adding a wide range of luxury skin care brands, including La Roche-Posay and Vichy, in four shops.
