Every time I speak for an audience, no matter what I say, there are abuses on social media calling for my candidacy to be rejected as a Member of Parliament for the next elections, condemning the politics of the Centre and telling me that I should not be a member of Labour.
And that's just what I'm going through.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments to my address are generally political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who every day have to deal with a flood of sexist or racist reactions, but are not intimidated.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era of politics is that it seems that bad abuses are considered normal.
Jeremy Corbyn claimed last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that broad church and with any ‘motion of distrust’ or change of selection rules the party becomes more petty.
For the past two years, I have often been advised to lay low, not just to express my opinion loudly and then I would ‘not get in trouble’.
But that's not what I went into politics for.
Since I joined Labour as a school child 32 years ago, provoked by the neglect of the Thatcher government, which literally caused my classroom to collapse, I have always argued for better public services for those who need them most, both in my role as a city councillor and in my role as a minister.
I never hid my politics, even in the last election.
Everyone in Nottingham East had clarity about my policy positions and my disagreements with the current leadership.
To those who promoted the motion on Friday, I can only say one thing: when the country moves on to a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But actually I have only one message, and it is not addressed to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are members of Labour or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that threats to reject my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election or political opportunities will not prevent me from acting according to what I think is in your interest.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
