It's a duty to win them back."
Throughout the country-circled Bolivia, the memory of the coastline that the country had to surrender to Chile after a bloody nineteenth-century conflict of raw materials is still vivid, as is the desire to re-enter the Pacific Ocean.
That hope may have reached its highest point in recent decades, as Bolivia is awaiting a ruling from the International Court of Justice, which should fall on 1 October after five years of deliberation.
‘Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and, of course, looks forward to the result with positive prospects’, said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians across the country will look at the Court's ruling on large screens, hoping that the Hague Tribunal will plead in favour of Bolivia that Chile, after decades of tough talks, is obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
Also for Evo Morales, the charismatic native president of Bolivia, who is facing a controversial re-election battle next year, much is at stake with the verdict of Monday.
‘We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,’ he swore at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favor of Bolivia, and even if it did, little would change.
The UN body established in the Netherlands does not have the authority to grant Chilean territory and has indicated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the ruling of the International Court of Justice falls only six months after the closing statement indicates that the case was ‘not complicated’, says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And the prospects for a positive outcome of Bolivia have certainly not improved, on the contrary, in the last four years the situation has perhaps even worsened.
‘The matter of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian government,’ Zárate said.
The warlike rhetoric of Morales has completely undermined all the goodwill that Chile might still have had, she claimed.
Bolivia and Chile will continue their talks at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to continue talking after this.
The two countries have not had an ambassador in each other's countries since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, representing Bolivia in The Hague, denies that the court's decision has been taken unusually quickly.
On Monday, Bolivia will ‘be given an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of international relations with Chile’ and an opportunity to ‘put an end to 139 years of disagreements, with mutual benefits’, he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents of Latin America, used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
