John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community-wide initiatives.
With over 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for secondary and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desired subjects par excellence within schools.
Nelson Mandela said: ‘If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
When you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and a relationship of trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent exam results, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated to SCIS, shows that 72 percent of the students achieved a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of the students in German, 69 percent of the students in French and 63 percent of the students in Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now as much valued as trade choice as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programmes and elsewhere.
A survey carried out by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that 17% of the obstacles to filling vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills are thus becoming increasingly important to prepare young people for their future careers.
As more and more job vacancies require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Communicating directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of over 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation. French was the only language that stood above 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today's children.
Speaking several languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the United Kingdom when they look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specialising in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot be denied at present that languages in a global business environment remain vital for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
