North Korea says that it will ‘under no circumstances’ unilaterally disarm without confidence
The Foreign Minister of North Korea told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued sanctions are leading to increasing distrust in the United States and that under such circumstances the country could under no circumstances unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN Annual General Assembly that over the past year North Korea had taken ‘significant goodwill measures’, such as stopping nuclear and missile testing, dismantling the site for nuclear testing and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
‘However, we do not see a similar reaction from the US’, he said.
‘Without any confidence in the US, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will under no circumstances unilaterally disarm ourselves.’
Although Ri repeated the known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to denuclearisation, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it took further steps, it was noted that he did not a priori disapprove of unilateral denuclearisation, as Pyongyang used to do.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work towards the ‘denuclearisation of the Korean Peninsula’, while Trump promised guarantees of North Korea’s security.
North Korea is aiming for a formal end to the Korea war of 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease the harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US insists on ‘denuclearisation first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way and even by objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of war’, said Ri.
‘The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an aircastle of the people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions only strengthen our mistrust.'
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the American leader suggested earlier in the week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: “If the other party had been South Korea on this issue of denuclearisation and not the USA, the denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a deadlock.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from last year when he said to the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles on the US mainland would be targeted after ‘Mr Evil President’ Trump Kim called a ‘missileman’ on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to completely destroy North Korea, praised Kim this year at the United Nations for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said that much remains to be done and that sanctions should remain until North Korea denuclearises.
On Wednesday Trump said that he had no timetable for this: ‘Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.’
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said to the UN Security Council on Thursday: ‘The enforcement of the sanctions of the Security Council must be vigorously and firmly continued until we have achieved the full, definitive, verified denuclearisation.’
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously implemented sanctions against North Korea to significantly reduce funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
Just a few hours after he left Pyongyang in July and said that progress had been made, North Korea accused him of making 'gangsterlike demands'.
This month, during a meeting with Moon, North Korea promised to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States took ‘consistent action’.
He said that Kim had told him that the ‘corresponding measures’ he wanted were security guarantees that Trump had promised in Singapore, and steps towards normalisation of relations with Washington.
Harvard students are taking a course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night and drink a lot of caffeine.
A professor noted that the students of the world's largest university often have no idea of the basic principles of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course. As far as he knows, it is unique in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech on the influence of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, "Why am I only getting to hear this in my senior year?"
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which will be organized for the first time this year, explains to the students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was established that students had a serious sleep deprivation during the week.
The course takes one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the parts, students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is influenced by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine when going to sleep.
In another part, participants are told how long - term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Using a map of the campus, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
‘We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know all this, just as people have the right to know the consequences of choosing cigarettes on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride on a night of study still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and increasing pressure on students sleep deprivation is an increasing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, of good quality, must be the ‘secret weapon’ of the student to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant hunger feeling.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to prepare the course, after all, he had taken lessons with the professor last year when he studied at Harvard in his first year.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before they come to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, and not just an alarm to stand up. They also need to be aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, which can make you difficult to fall asleep.
