Almanak: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from the almanac of our Sunday Morning: 30 September 1882, today exactly 136 years ago, for those who can TELL well... the day on which future physicist Johannes Wilhelm ‘Hans’ Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device called Geiger counter.
Since then, the Geiger counter has not been able to think away from science, and also became an icon in pop culture, for example in ‘Bells or Coronado’, a 1950 film with the initially unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: ‘What the hell is that?’
Rogers: ‘That’s a Geiger counter, which is used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you hear the effect of the atoms released by the radioactivity in the minerals.'
Evans: ‘It’s really banging now!’
‘Hans’ Geiger died in 1945, barely a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains relevant.
