The Global Citizen Festival, which was first organised in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, a group of international advocators who hope to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting against it.
Concertgoers who want to obtain a free ticket for the event (unless they were willing to pay for a VIP card), had to complete a series of tasks, or 'actions', such as volunteering, e-mailing a world leader, making a phone call or in another meaningful way raising awareness for the purpose: an end to poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been, with 12 more years to go to achieve this goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a suitable way to convince people to demand a call for action or is this just another form of 'click-tivism', giving people the feeling that they are making a real contribution by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, according to Global Citizen, more than 19 million 'actions' of supporters have been registered, targeting a large number of different targets.
According to Global Citizen, these actions have contributed to the commitment of world leaders and to policy proposals worth more than $37 billion to change the lives of 2.25 billion people by 2030.
Early in 2018, the group quoted 390 initiatives and statements based on the actions, of which at least $10 billion has been paid or brought together by sponsor actions.
The group estimates that the funds obtained so far have had an impact on almost 649 million people around the world.
Among the main declarations of intent are those of The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of investors and executives from the United Kingdom with the aim of 'helping children realise their full potential'. This group has pledged $35 million to Rwanda to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the help of the British government, of donors, of other national governments and of Global Citizens like you, we can make the social injustice that is malnutrition a footnote in history," said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of The Power of Nutrition, the audience at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also announced that, after more than 5,000 actions were sent in which the British government was asked to improve the nutritional situation for mothers and children, the government has announced to support a project, the Power of Nutrition, that will reach 5 million women and children with nutritional interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the Global Citizen website that asked "why do you think we can end extreme poverty?"
The group replied: "It will be a long and difficult road, sometimes falling and failing.
But, like civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will ultimately be successful because we are stronger together.
