The only clergyman of the Church of England who acquired a Victoria Cross during World War I as a military man is honored 100 years later in his hometown.
Lieutenant-Colonel, Father Bernard Vann received the award following the attack at Bellenglise and Lehaucourt on 29 September 1918.
Four days later, however, he was killed by a sniper and never knew that he had been given the highest British military honor.
A memorial stone was unveiled by his two grandsons during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of the grandsons, Michael Vann, said that it was 'brilliant symbolic' that the stone was revealed exactly 100 years after the fact for which his grandfather had been distinguished.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion over the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in a very dense fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns.
He later rushed to the line of fire and led the line forward before running to a field gun alone and eliminating three members of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over one month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "something that I know I can never match, but also something that makes me feel humble".
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also laid a wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
