Germany's new warship postponed again
The latest frigate of the German Navy should have been in service in 2014, replacing the outdated warships of the Cold War, but it will take at least one year before it is ready, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the 'Rheinland-Pfalz', the leading ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit that quotes a military spokesman.
The vessel should have been part of the Navy in 2014, but the worrying problems after delivery have plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ordered by the Navy in 2007 are intended to replace the outdated frigates of the Bremen class.
As far as we know, they have a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft missiles and a form of stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic characteristics.
Other important features are longer maintenance cycles, it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates up to two years in a row, far away from home ports.
However, the constant delays mean that the advanced warships, which are intended to allow Germany to project its overseas power, are already obsolete by the time they are put into operation, notes Die Zeit.
The fateful frigate F125 already made the headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy sent a ship back to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons behind this return, but German media cited a number of crucial 'software and hardware defects' that would render the warship useless if it were deployed in a combat mission.
Software defects were especially important because the boats of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class are operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, half the manpower on the frigates of the older Bremen class.
It also became clear that the ship is suffering from severe overweight, which will reduce performance and limit the capabilities of the Navy to carry out further upgrades.
The 'Rheinland-Pfalz' weighs 7,000 tons, which is twice as much as ships of a similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the price tag for the entire project, including the training of the crew, is already a problem.
It is said that this has reached a staggering €3.1 billion compared to the original €2.2 billion.
The problems that the latest frigates have in their grip are becoming extra important because of the recent warnings that the power of the German Navy is diminishing.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the Parliamentary Defence Commission in Germany, acknowledged that the Navy is in fact "a shortage of deployable ships".
The official said that the problem has grown over time as a snowball, because old ships were taken out of operation but no replacement vessels were delivered.
He complained that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class were yet available for inclusion in the Navy.
National Trust tracks the secret life of bats
New research carried out on an estate in the Scottish Highlands, attempts to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown large-ear bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
NTS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the cries of the bat and what kind of what does it do.
A map of the habitat and a report is then produced to create a detailed landscape-scale image of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation advisor, hopes that the results will show which habitat areas are the most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making meadows and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have fallen significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping accommodations and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightnings can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
At the NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly carry out surveys, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much about bats is not yet known, and that is why the work we do here and at other locations will help us to better understand what they need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance work was carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, possibly destroying a full local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them or destroy their sleeping accommodations.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to contribute to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and of many of our species we simply don't know how their populations are."
