The most recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (Florida Commission for the Conservation of Fish and Fauna) shows a general decrease in concentrations of Red glow in parts of Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the US).
According to the committee, it is reported that there is a fragmentary increase in the Red glow in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier provinces, which could indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The Red glow extends over an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
There are about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County spots, but in fewer places than last week.
Red glow was also seen in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported off the coast of Pinellas County last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier provinces.
